content.description: Start with a rail at chest height. Climb the left side of the rounded northeast arête, using small crimps all the way up.
content.location: This is on the westerly of the two boulders.

content.description: Climb the varnished features in the middle of the arête.
content.location: This is on the westerly of the two boulders. With your back to the easterly boulder, proceed to the left arête and look for the most varnished features.

content.description: Stand start matched on edge feature and work up  through crimps and sidepulls, eventually reaching an easy top out heading up and left.
content.location: This line goes up the right side of the southeastern face of the second twin towers boulder.

content.description: Stand start. Climb the tall east face. There are multiple variations.
content.location: This is on the westerly of the two boulders. It's the furthest right on the arête problems, left of the V2.

content.description: Start on the crimpy side pulls, get up to the slopey jug (or the juggy sloper, whatever), and follow the crack line up to good holds at the top. Powerful for shorter climbers.
content.location: This is on the easterly of the two boulders.

content.description: Start start use large blocky holds, continue straight up on good holds the whole way.
content.location: Start About 5 feet right of freedom fighter

content.description: Perhaps a bit contrived, possibly just a variation of Left Arête. Nevertheless, it's in the guidebook, so I suppose it's an established boulder problem. Climb the leftmost possible ascent of the most varnished features.
content.location: This is on the westerly of the two boulders. With your back to the easterly boulder, proceed around the corner of the left arête to the backside.

content.description: Sunny until the afternoon. Good sandstone with some featured chickenhead topouts.
